\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs22\lang9 In researching the concept of hashing for the purpose of the assignment, one important thing I learned is the limitations of linear probing relative to chaining (using a linked list). A linear probing hash table must be at least as large as the data being hashed, but preferably meaningfully larger, firstly due to the fact that collisions will cause the function to overrun the top of the table and go out of range without a means to loop back around. Secondly, the efficiency of such a hash table decreases as the "load factor" (percentage of taken slots) approaches 100%; in many cases, when a collision occurs, the item being hashed will get shunted far enough that it encroaches into the hash space that should belong to a different key, requiring iteration through many items unrelated by hash to get there when searching. \par
The first function I used was a very simple one that hashed items according to the position of their first letter in the alphabet, and put edge cases (Unicode characters, numbers, symbols) into one bucket, requiring 27 buckets in the linked list. This wasn't designed with linear probing in mind at all since all but the first 27 insertions would be collisions, and the results reflect that. In theory, this should cut the search time in 1/27th in a worst case scenario in the linked list method.\par
The second function, also very bad for linear probing, summed the positions of the first eight letters, or all letters if there weren't eight. Since "zzzzzzzz" would be hashed as 200, anything above 200 or below 0 was treated as an edge case and put into a dedicated bucket, 201. The advantage of the first two is that we know how large the linked list list needs to be, so there is no wasted space. I noticed more 201s than I expected with the sentinel print activated, which is probably due to space characters taking the number below zero.\par
The last function summed the full ASCII values (not minus 97) of all characters, and relied on the modulo to shrink the key below the size of the hash table.\cf1\f1\par
