\cf0\f0 I then tried a new hashing method that I had come across in my research, XOR hash, which was supposedly more random than additive hash. I found that it tended to create low numbers only (around 300 at most), so I modified it by multiplying the result by one one-hundredth of the hash table size before moduloing it. The resulting widely spaced results (by increments of 10), combined with the table size of double the data size in this experiment, are a good thing for linear probing, as the drastically lower construction time shows, but result in undesirable wasted space and clustering when using linked lists.\cf1\f1\par
